WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.190 --> 00:00:04.090
MALE SPEAKER: We are
glad to have here

00:00:04.090 --> 00:00:05.500
Professor N. T. Wright.

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:09.240
He is the former bishop of
Durham, which, if I am correct,

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:13.440
that makes you the House
of Lords, currently,

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:18.900
but most well known for being a
Biblical scholar and the author

00:00:18.900 --> 00:00:20.490
of numerous texts.

00:00:20.490 --> 00:00:22.250
I believe it's 50
different books

00:00:22.250 --> 00:00:24.880
you have [INAUDIBLE] all on
New Testament scholarship

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:26.760
and religious studies.

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:28.930
So I won't exhaust this.

00:00:28.930 --> 00:00:32.090
He is, for many, does
not need an introduction,

00:00:32.090 --> 00:00:34.860
so yes, we're excited
to have you here.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:36.355
So welcome, Professor Wright.

00:00:36.355 --> 00:00:37.285
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:37.285 --> 00:00:38.725
N. T. WRIGHT: Thank
you very much.

00:00:38.725 --> 00:00:39.225
Thank you.

00:00:44.407 --> 00:00:45.240
Thank you very much.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:48.279
It's a surprise and
a delight to be here.

00:00:48.279 --> 00:00:50.570
Google for me is something
that comes up on the screen,

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:52.550
and actually thinking
of it as a place, never

00:00:52.550 --> 00:00:54.380
mind a campus,
never mind people,

00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:56.040
is kind of blowing
my mind right now,

00:00:56.040 --> 00:00:57.810
and I'm very happy about that.

00:00:57.810 --> 00:01:00.460
I'm also happy about the fact
that whereas in my previous job

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:02.270
when I was Bishop
of Durham, almost

00:01:02.270 --> 00:01:05.170
every church meeting I
went to, I significantly

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:07.860
reduced the average
age of those present,

00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:10.810
I think now I'm
significantly increasing

00:01:10.810 --> 00:01:11.960
the average age of those.

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:14.430
I suspect I'm at least
twice as old as most of you

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:16.472
here in this room, and
I'm very happy about that.

00:01:16.472 --> 00:01:18.429
It reminds me that I'm
on my way to retirement,

00:01:18.429 --> 00:01:20.730
and listening to music, and
playing on the golf course,

00:01:20.730 --> 00:01:21.295
and so on.

00:01:21.295 --> 00:01:23.170
But at the moment, I'm
still bouncing around,

00:01:23.170 --> 00:01:25.503
talking about God, and Jesus,
and the Bible, and church,

00:01:25.503 --> 00:01:28.670
and the world, and
culture, and what we

00:01:28.670 --> 00:01:30.030
should be doing in our culture.

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:32.040
And since you people are
part of the people who

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:35.340
are shaping the way that
people-- not only what people

00:01:35.340 --> 00:01:37.950
think about, but the
way people think,

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:40.640
what I want to try to
do today is to put out

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:43.580
some parameters to
do with how I think

00:01:43.580 --> 00:01:46.680
the gospel, the Christian
good news, actually works,

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:48.840
and then to reflect
just a little

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:52.930
on what being human within
that good news might look like

00:01:52.930 --> 00:01:57.650
and what, as humans, we ought
to be doing in order to engage

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:00.770
with the wider world in a way
which is wise, and honest,

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:02.390
and actually deeply Christian.

00:02:02.390 --> 00:02:05.390
The idea of Christians
engaging with the world at all

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:07.270
has often been at a discount.

00:02:07.270 --> 00:02:09.810
People think, well, I don't
really belong in this world.

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:11.130
I have a spiritual identity.

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:12.600
I'm off someplace else.

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:15.980
And actually, that is deeply
un-Biblical, deeply untrue

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:18.000
to the Jewish and
Christian vision.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:19.850
I'll explain in a moment.

00:02:19.850 --> 00:02:22.370
But let me say one or two
things about good news.

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:24.920
I have a book coming out,
which has just come out,

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:27.400
called "Simply Good News."

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:30.320
I'm not sure it's actually as
simple as some people think,

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:31.990
but I'm trying to
make it simple.

00:02:31.990 --> 00:02:33.830
But the main
message of that book

00:02:33.830 --> 00:02:36.780
is that contrary to
popular imagination,

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:40.550
the Christian message is
good news, not good advice,

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:42.290
and there is all
sorts of difference

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:45.230
between news and advice.

00:02:45.230 --> 00:02:47.950
And news is a funny
sort of thing.

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:49.890
Many people think
you go to church

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:52.360
in order to get good
advice about how to live.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:53.800
Well, maybe you
do, but that's not

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:57.060
the main point-- or good
advice about how to reorder

00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:58.520
your private spirituality.

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:01.130
Well, that, again, may
happen, but that's not

00:03:01.130 --> 00:03:03.930
the whole point of it--
or even good advice

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:07.580
about which technique to
be sure you plug into so

00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:10.540
that after your death, you
go to the right destination.

00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:12.810
Well, again, that
seems pretty important,

00:03:12.810 --> 00:03:16.070
but that sounds like
advice rather than news.

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:18.840
News is about
something that happens,

00:03:18.840 --> 00:03:23.520
as a result of which the world
is a different place, often

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:26.830
in ways that people don't
expect, sometimes in ways

00:03:26.830 --> 00:03:28.700
that they don't want.

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:32.260
You all know where you were
on September the 11th, 2001.

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:35.230
I bet you don't know where
you were on November the 22nd,

00:03:35.230 --> 00:03:37.040
2003.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:40.450
I know exactly where I. I was
in a hotel room in Atlanta,

00:03:40.450 --> 00:03:43.520
Georgia, and I phoned home
at 5:00 in the morning

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:45.390
because the television
screens were not

00:03:45.390 --> 00:03:47.510
showing the event
that I wanted to see,

00:03:47.510 --> 00:03:50.120
which was the final
of the Rugby World Cup

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:53.480
because England were playing
Australia in Australia,

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:55.210
and nothing Australians
like more than

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:57.820
to beat the British at
one of their sports.

00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:00.610
So I was naturally-- England
had made it to the final,

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:03.580
astonishingly, so I was
on pins to find out.

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:06.960
And I knew my daughter would
be glued to the television,

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:08.940
so I phoned her at
the appointed hour.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:09.990
Oh, Dad, it's terrible.

00:04:09.990 --> 00:04:12.204
It's gone to full time,
and the score is 17-all,

00:04:12.204 --> 00:04:13.870
and they have to play
another half-hour,

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:17.399
and it's all very tense,
and-- so I got up,

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:19.953
and I paced around, and I
waited for half an hour,

00:04:19.953 --> 00:04:22.350
and I phoned her
again, and hey, yay, we

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:24.250
won on the last
kick of the match.

00:04:24.250 --> 00:04:27.100
Jonny Wilkinson, who was the
poster boy of English rugby,

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:28.320
had done a drop goal.

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:29.920
And as a result,
England had won,

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:33.240
and Australia were decimated.

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:35.590
And then I had a dilemma.

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:40.860
I was in a semi-dark hall in
a hotel in Atlanta, Georgia,

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.570
and I wanted to go up and
hug the hall porter and say

00:04:43.570 --> 00:04:45.070
did you hear we
won the World Cup?

00:04:45.070 --> 00:04:47.471
And I went, he probably
doesn't know what rugby is.

00:04:47.471 --> 00:04:48.970
He may not even
know where Australia

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:51.400
is, let alone anything else.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:55.500
So I wanted to tell the check-in
clerks, did you hear the news?

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:59.209
And I realized this means
nothing to them whatever,

00:04:59.209 --> 00:05:01.250
and I was waiting for
somebody to come downstairs

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:04.860
to the conference who knew that
there had been a game going on.

00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:07.870
And finally, somebody did,
and it was an Australian.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:12.390
So I had this good
news, which was

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:15.180
foolishness to the Americans,
scandalous to the Australians,

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:19.400
but for those of us who
believed, it made us happy

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:19.900
all year.

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:23.850
And one of the effects
was hundreds, thousands

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:25.830
of little English
boys, and at least

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:28.270
hundreds of little
English girls,

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:29.940
wanted to be Jonny
Wilkinson when

00:05:29.940 --> 00:05:32.430
they grew up and
would be practicing

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:35.210
drop goals in the schoolyard.

00:05:35.210 --> 00:05:39.094
Something had happened,
as a result of which,

00:05:39.094 --> 00:05:40.260
everything looked different.

00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:42.490
Now, of course, in
sport, that doesn't last.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:45.036
We haven't been to-- one
of my Australian friends

00:05:45.036 --> 00:05:46.410
who read this book
and saw that I

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:49.817
used that story upfront sent me
a rude email saying you wait.

00:05:49.817 --> 00:05:51.900
You won't be using too
many more of those stories.

00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:53.940
We'll get you.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:55.570
I did actually send--
when it happened,

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:57.990
I sent him an email
congratulating the Australians

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:00.370
on being such good
losers, and he sent one

00:06:00.370 --> 00:06:03.310
straight back saying, yeah,
considering how little practice

00:06:03.310 --> 00:06:06.260
we have at it-- at
losing, that is.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:08.170
But you see, news
is about something

00:06:08.170 --> 00:06:10.880
that's happened, as a
result of which the world is

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:13.750
a different place, and
as a result of which

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:15.370
things kind of fracture.

00:06:15.370 --> 00:06:19.080
Some people say this doesn't
make any sense in our world.

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:21.540
Other people say this
makes all the wrong kind

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:22.840
of sense in my world.

00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:26.950
But some people find that
it transforms their lives.

00:06:26.950 --> 00:06:29.320
And in the early Christian
world, that's what happened.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.450
How did it transform
their lives?

00:06:31.450 --> 00:06:33.090
What was going on?

00:06:33.090 --> 00:06:38.090
Well, the gospel, the good
news, is a message about Jesus,

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:40.540
but so many people
have put that message

00:06:40.540 --> 00:06:44.020
within an implicit
back story, which

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:47.220
makes it different from how
the early Christians saw it.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:49.060
You see, my back
story was that I'd

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:51.450
been following English
rugby since the days when,

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:53.982
believe it or not, I played
rugby myself as a teenager.

00:06:53.982 --> 00:06:56.440
I've been interested in what
they're doing, following them.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:06:57.930
I knew the back story.

00:06:57.930 --> 00:06:59.980
The Australians knew
their back story,

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:01.470
and those two were
going to clash.

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:04.710
The Americans in Atlanta
had no back story at all,

00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:06.570
no interest--
didn't mean a thing.

00:07:06.570 --> 00:07:08.900
I might as well go out on
the street in St. Andrews

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:11.460
and say that, I don't know,
Duke have beaten Caltech

00:07:11.460 --> 00:07:13.040
at basketball or something.

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:15.860
People just aren't terribly
interested in [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:17.010
I'm sorry about that.

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:21.440
What's the back story?

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:25.350
The back story for so many
people, both inside the church

00:07:25.350 --> 00:07:28.730
and outside, goes
like this, that there

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:31.966
is this dangerous God
somewhere up in the sky, maybe.

00:07:31.966 --> 00:07:32.590
We're not sure.

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:35.010
But if there is, he's dangerous.

00:07:35.010 --> 00:07:37.490
He's made a very
high moral bar, which

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:40.200
he wants us all to jump over.

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:42.460
We've all failed to jump
over that moral bar,

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:44.410
so he's out to get us.

00:07:44.410 --> 00:07:46.220
But then, at the last
minute, fortunately,

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:50.351
somebody else steps in the
way, takes a hit in our place.

00:07:50.351 --> 00:07:51.350
Phew, so it's all right.

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:53.200
And it happens to
be his own son.

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:55.010
So somehow, that's OK.

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:57.560
Now, I have not yet
found a preacher who

00:07:57.560 --> 00:08:00.420
admits to having preached
the gospel like that,

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:04.130
but I know many, many people
in many, many churches

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:06.810
for whom that is what
they've actually heard.

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:12.440
That's what they think more
or less the message is about.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:15.360
The back story, actually,
is very different to that.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:17.710
The back story is
about a good world,

00:08:17.710 --> 00:08:20.810
a good God who made
a good world and who

00:08:20.810 --> 00:08:24.870
made human beings to be
within his good world

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:28.120
as people who would
bring wisdom, and order,

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:31.500
and flourishing, and
possibility to that world

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.330
to develop his creation.

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:35.870
He says be fruitful and multiply
and look after the world.

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:37.659
Name the animals.

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:40.900
Tend the garden.

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:44.110
And who would sum up the
praises of the world,

00:08:44.110 --> 00:08:46.680
the praises of the trees,
and the season, the animals,

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:49.960
and so on, and present them in
articulate speech before God.

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:52.850
This is the vocation
of being human,

00:08:52.850 --> 00:08:55.780
and that vocation remains--
come back to that in a moment.

00:08:55.780 --> 00:09:00.500
But when humans mess up and say,
no, we don't want to do that.

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:02.029
We've got our own
way of doing this,

00:09:02.029 --> 00:09:04.320
and we're going to manipulate
the world in our own way,

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:05.153
thank you very much.

00:09:05.153 --> 00:09:08.690
And, well, God, if there is a
God, you can do your own thing.

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:12.210
The results of that is not that
you have a big, bad, angry God

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:14.830
with a big stick about
to beat us over the head,

00:09:14.830 --> 00:09:18.890
but that the project for
the creation as a whole

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:20.930
is out of joint.

00:09:20.930 --> 00:09:24.420
You see that in 100, maybe
1,000 different ways,

00:09:24.420 --> 00:09:27.330
both in the Bible and,
of course, in our world.

00:09:27.330 --> 00:09:29.800
Now, there are many, many
mysteries about this.

00:09:29.800 --> 00:09:32.400
I'm not saying that
human rebellion

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:34.170
causes, say, earthquakes.

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:38.910
A tectonic plate does what a
tectonic plate does, and so on.

00:09:38.910 --> 00:09:41.340
However, many, many
things have gone

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:46.480
radically wrong in the world as
a result of human brokenness.

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:49.270
And the plan, the back
story, is about God

00:09:49.270 --> 00:09:52.670
dealing with the human
brokenness in order

00:09:52.670 --> 00:09:54.250
to put the world right.

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:59.360
In other words, God the
creator promises and intends

00:09:59.360 --> 00:10:01.720
to put the world
right, and so He

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:05.420
puts us right in
the present in order

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:08.860
that we can be part of
his putting-right project

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:09.920
for the world.

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:11.830
That's how the story works.

00:10:11.830 --> 00:10:13.650
And within that,
you get, if you're

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:15.880
a traditional Christian
with theories of atonement,

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:18.370
incarnation,
resurrection, et cetera,

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:20.270
et cetera, you get all of that.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:21.670
In fact, you get it enhanced.

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:24.680
It makes more sense of
your traditional frameworks

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:29.260
and texts, not less.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:31.810
But what this leaves
us with is a vision

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:35.830
of a world with the
creator putting it right,

00:10:35.830 --> 00:10:39.040
doing so through Jesus,
and then promising

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:41.870
that what He did through
Jesus-- uniquely one-off--

00:10:41.870 --> 00:10:45.880
that's the news about the
event that actually happened.

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:49.790
What he did with Jesus,
He will do in the future

00:10:49.790 --> 00:10:51.230
for the whole creation.

00:10:51.230 --> 00:10:54.160
Hence, the death and
resurrection of Jesus

00:10:54.160 --> 00:10:57.470
point forward to the
ultimate event, which

00:10:57.470 --> 00:10:59.480
is God putting the
whole world right,

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:03.720
and we are held in between
the one event and the other.

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:06.230
This is where the rugby story
doesn't work quite so well.

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:09.310
Another story which I use in
the book, and which I developed,

00:11:09.310 --> 00:11:11.190
is the ancient
historical story of what

00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:15.260
happened after Julius Caesar's
assassination in 44 BC.

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:18.730
His heir and putative
successor, Octavian,

00:11:18.730 --> 00:11:21.020
ended up in a civil
war against Antony,

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:23.020
who'd been one of
Caesar's best friends,

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:25.510
because they could tell the
big prize was out there.

00:11:25.510 --> 00:11:28.220
Only one of them
would be the big dog

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:32.000
in this great superpower that
was the early Roman Empire.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.620
And finally-- and
all the Roman world

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:36.242
was on tiptoe
waiting to see what

00:11:36.242 --> 00:11:38.200
would happen because half
of them were with one

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:40.460
and half of them were with
the other, and half of them

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:44.070
hated them both, and it
was all very confusing.

00:11:44.070 --> 00:11:46.920
Finally, Octavian defeated
Antony at the Battle of Actium,

00:11:46.920 --> 00:11:48.770
and Antony and Cleopatra
went back to Egypt,

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:50.760
where they died not
long afterwards.

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:53.060
And then, Octavian had
to go around all the bits

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:54.920
that needed mopping
up and sorting out

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:56.260
before coming back to Rome.

00:11:56.260 --> 00:11:57.824
But the word would
get back to Rome--

00:11:57.824 --> 00:11:59.740
and this is the point
of my telling the story.

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:02.710
Something has happened, as a
result of which the world is

00:12:02.710 --> 00:12:04.020
a different place.

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:05.430
Octavian has won.

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:07.330
He's now going to be in charge.

00:12:07.330 --> 00:12:10.120
You better get your head round
that one and your allegiance

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:11.250
sorted out.

00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:12.490
Something will happen.

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:14.380
He's coming back
to Rome when he's

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:16.400
sorted out all the other stuff.

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:19.760
And anyone living in
Rome between the victory

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:22.540
at Actium in 31 and
Octavian's return

00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:25.260
three years later
would know that they

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:28.680
had to order their lives
in accordance with the fact

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:31.976
that now there was a
different system obtaining.

00:12:31.976 --> 00:12:34.350
Something has happened, as a
result of which the world is

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:35.170
a different place.

00:12:35.170 --> 00:12:37.540
Something will happen,
which will complete that,

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:40.980
and we live in between the two.

00:12:40.980 --> 00:12:43.850
So when as a Christian I say,
well, something has happened.

00:12:43.850 --> 00:12:46.610
This is the death and
resurrection of Jesus,

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:51.390
and the gift of this strange,
mysterious, sometimes intimate,

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:53.210
sometimes frightening
force that we

00:12:53.210 --> 00:12:57.530
call the Holy Spirit-- the
interval between those gifts

00:12:57.530 --> 00:13:01.140
and the final putting right of
all things is where we live,

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:05.130
and that's where the human
vocation gets restored.

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:07.330
And the human vocation
in the New Testament

00:13:07.330 --> 00:13:10.170
will be, again, to
be image bearers.

00:13:10.170 --> 00:13:11.950
The image-- by the
way, many of you

00:13:11.950 --> 00:13:13.730
may have heard this
language about being

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:16.180
in the image of God, and there
are all sorts of theories

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:17.580
about what that means.

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:19.970
Biblical scholars now are
increasingly convinced

00:13:19.970 --> 00:13:22.640
that what it means is
that humans are designed

00:13:22.640 --> 00:13:27.040
to be a kind of angled
mirror so that you reflect

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:30.790
God out into the world--
think of the angled mirror--

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:33.980
and you reflect the
world back to God.

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:36.775
And when humans go wrong, it's
when they turn the mirror so

00:13:36.775 --> 00:13:39.140
that it reflects the
world back to the world,

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:41.530
and then you go around
in a fairly deadly cycle

00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:44.560
because the world does
not have life in itself.

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:46.200
It's a God-given life.

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:50.530
So the human task is
to bring God's wisdom

00:13:50.530 --> 00:13:53.620
and flourishing to
the world to make

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:57.340
the-- there's an old joke in my
country about a clergyman who's

00:13:57.340 --> 00:13:58.850
walking down the
street, and he sees

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:00.320
somebody digging the garden.

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:02.000
And he says, isn't
it wonderful what

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.170
can happen when providence and
the hand of man get together

00:14:05.170 --> 00:14:06.250
and work on something?

00:14:06.250 --> 00:14:08.541
And the gardener says, you
should have seen this garden

00:14:08.541 --> 00:14:11.470
when providence had it
all to itself, because

00:14:11.470 --> 00:14:14.010
of course, what's sad
about-- and actually, it's

00:14:14.010 --> 00:14:14.706
a silly joke.

00:14:14.706 --> 00:14:16.580
It's a well-known joke,
but it's a silly joke

00:14:16.580 --> 00:14:19.780
because in a Christian or
Jewish doctrine of providence,

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:22.970
the way God wanted to work
in the world, large scale

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:27.950
and small scale, is in so many
cases through human beings.

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:30.010
Of course, you and I
didn't make the sunrise

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:32.490
or the moonrise last
night or this morning.

00:14:32.490 --> 00:14:35.040
You and I don't do an awful lot
of things which nevertheless

00:14:35.040 --> 00:14:36.010
happen in the world.

00:14:36.010 --> 00:14:39.540
But the way God wants
this world to flourish

00:14:39.540 --> 00:14:43.290
is by wise human beings
taking responsibility,

00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:46.250
doing things which will
bring that flourishing

00:14:46.250 --> 00:14:48.840
to the world, which is
where you guys come in

00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:51.830
because of course, the
world needs information.

00:14:51.830 --> 00:14:52.370
Thank you.

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:54.750
We get much more
of it as a result

00:14:54.750 --> 00:14:56.430
of what you do,
actually much more

00:14:56.430 --> 00:14:57.800
than we can possibly cope with.

00:14:57.800 --> 00:15:00.030
It's like drinking
from a fire hydrant.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:02.320
And whereas when I
was a young scholar,

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:03.820
I would trudge off
to the library,

00:15:03.820 --> 00:15:05.750
and I would get a
heavy, dusty volume out,

00:15:05.750 --> 00:15:08.469
and I would look up something
and take half the morning

00:15:08.469 --> 00:15:10.760
and then go and have a cup
of coffee to think about it,

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:14.270
I now just go brrmph, and
there it is on the screen,

00:15:14.270 --> 00:15:17.770
although, of course, sometimes
I get conflicting information,

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:20.140
even from you guys,
so that's something

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:21.400
one has to be careful about.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:24.470
But information
generally, obviously,

00:15:24.470 --> 00:15:26.700
is a very, very,
very good thing.

00:15:26.700 --> 00:15:30.700
And information-- the gathering,
collecting, and disseminating

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:32.700
of information
seems to me always

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:35.910
has been actually a vital
part of the human task.

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:38.100
That's why education
is something

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:40.950
which the Jewish and Christian
traditions have always

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:44.480
insisted on as being paramount,
not just for the elite,

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:48.220
but for everyone within reach,
that actually giving people

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:52.040
the information about the world,
about themselves, about life

00:15:52.040 --> 00:15:53.370
is enabling.

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:55.750
It's part of human flourishing.

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:57.300
And suddenly,
something's happened

00:15:57.300 --> 00:16:00.220
in this last generation as
a result of everything here

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:02.900
and in this surrounding
area, as a result of which,

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:05.920
the world as a whole
is far better informed

00:16:05.920 --> 00:16:07.972
than it's ever been.

00:16:07.972 --> 00:16:10.180
I suppose the question that
I have about that-- well,

00:16:10.180 --> 00:16:12.570
I have many questions
about it, one of which is,

00:16:12.570 --> 00:16:16.120
what changes when, instead
of walking to the library,

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:18.740
thinking about something,
looking it up, going and having

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:20.840
a coffee and thinking
about, then going back

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:24.360
to work-- instead of that, it
takes me three seconds to find

00:16:24.360 --> 00:16:26.460
it through Google or whatever.

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:29.360
Something's changed about
the way we do research,

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:31.520
and I'm not sure that
any of us have really

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:33.660
come to terms with that yet.

00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:36.680
Whether we have the time
to reflect that we used to,

00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:39.367
or whether this just does
create more time to reflect

00:16:39.367 --> 00:16:41.700
because there's less walking
around and sitting drinking

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:43.100
coffee, whatever-- well, maybe.

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:46.370
We still walk around
and drink coffee.

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:48.820
But in the middle of that,
there's a difference--

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:50.490
obviously, as you
know as well as I do,

00:16:50.490 --> 00:16:54.620
but I want to draw it out--
between information and wisdom.

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:56.910
And what we find in the
Bible very interestingly

00:16:56.910 --> 00:16:59.060
is this famous character
called Solomon,

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:01.690
one of the early
great kings of Israel.

00:17:01.690 --> 00:17:03.990
Well, he had problems
at a certain point,

00:17:03.990 --> 00:17:06.760
but basically, a really
extraordinary human being

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:07.790
in the tradition.

00:17:07.790 --> 00:17:10.359
And Solomon, we
are told, collected

00:17:10.359 --> 00:17:13.510
information like nobody
had ever done before.

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:16.500
He knew all about the trees,
and the flowers, and the birds,

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:17.349
and the animals.

00:17:17.349 --> 00:17:19.190
He knew all about
what we would call

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:22.380
the encyclopedia of
information known to humans,

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:23.589
and he collected this.

00:17:23.589 --> 00:17:26.690
He had folk who went out
and gathered information.

00:17:26.690 --> 00:17:29.840
All sorts of stuff he knew,
and he could teach it,

00:17:29.840 --> 00:17:31.670
and he could inform people.

00:17:31.670 --> 00:17:34.940
But interestingly, none of
that stuff is in the Bible.

00:17:34.940 --> 00:17:38.000
I would love to have Solomon's
lists of trees and animals.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.060
That would be brilliant.

00:17:39.060 --> 00:17:40.010
But we don't.

00:17:40.010 --> 00:17:43.370
What we have instead is a book
called Proverbs, some of which

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:46.370
may go back to Solomon, but
it's the Solomonic tradition.

00:17:46.370 --> 00:17:50.070
And Proverbs has a certain
amount of information,

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:54.690
but it's actually-- how do you
steer through this minefield

00:17:54.690 --> 00:17:55.610
of information?

00:17:55.610 --> 00:17:58.600
How do you navigate
a wise course?

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:01.160
How do you know which to choose?

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:03.100
When all this
information is out there,

00:18:03.100 --> 00:18:07.770
how do you know what you should
do now in this human situation?

00:18:07.770 --> 00:18:11.450
And of course, if I Google
for advice on something,

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:13.710
I'm sure there'll be all
sorts of websites that'll

00:18:13.710 --> 00:18:16.030
come up telling me exactly
how to do everything

00:18:16.030 --> 00:18:19.594
from planting a tree to fixing
a card to whatever it may be I

00:18:19.594 --> 00:18:20.760
want to do-- cooking a meal.

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:23.480
I'm told there are now people
whose entire repertoire

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:26.910
of cookery is what they find
online, recipes and so on.

00:18:26.910 --> 00:18:28.150
Fortunately, I'm not a cook.

00:18:28.150 --> 00:18:30.010
I say fortunately for
the sake of my family

00:18:30.010 --> 00:18:34.210
so that I don't do that, but
I can see how useful that is.

00:18:34.210 --> 00:18:36.030
But the point is that
the book of Proverbs

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:39.170
and the whole wisdom
tradition, which comes through

00:18:39.170 --> 00:18:41.340
into the New
Testament and beyond,

00:18:41.340 --> 00:18:43.720
is not simply about information.

00:18:43.720 --> 00:18:46.600
It's about wisdom,
and at the heart of it

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:49.980
is that rather strange
old line which says,

00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:53.050
"The fear of the Lord is
the beginning of wisdom."

00:18:53.050 --> 00:18:54.670
And I need to say
quickly in brackets

00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:58.950
that the word "fear" doesn't
mean a panicky, cringing fear.

00:18:58.950 --> 00:19:00.250
It means reverence.

00:19:00.250 --> 00:19:04.630
It means recognizing that God
is God and that I'm not God.

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:07.170
And it seems to be the
danger with so many aspects

00:19:07.170 --> 00:19:09.950
of our culture-- and this
isn't a cheap shot at you

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:12.540
and what you do because
actually, it affects all of us

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:15.580
in one sort or another-- is
that we think by gathering

00:19:15.580 --> 00:19:17.550
information, we're in charge.

00:19:17.550 --> 00:19:19.420
We are controlling this.

00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:22.280
The equivalent I see in
my culture, interestingly,

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:25.180
over the 1990s and then
on into the early years

00:19:25.180 --> 00:19:27.780
of the present century
is that whenever

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:30.070
there was a problem in
my society, at least,

00:19:30.070 --> 00:19:32.380
and I think this
happened in America too,

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:34.880
somebody in government
and in the civil service

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:38.560
thought it was a good idea to
get us to fill in forms, often

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:42.040
in triplicate, and to sign
off on them so that everything

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:46.560
you did had a paper trail which
ended up in somebody's office

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:47.840
files somewhere.

00:19:47.840 --> 00:19:49.850
And we all used to
grumble and say,

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:52.100
are we going to be given
extra secretaries to do this?

00:19:52.100 --> 00:19:53.808
And the answer was
no, can't afford that.

00:19:53.808 --> 00:19:56.250
So everyone's
workload just secretly

00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:58.320
expands into more
and more paperwork,

00:19:58.320 --> 00:20:01.140
as though by the
gathering of information,

00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:03.770
we will make sure that we're
all behaving properly and doing

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:04.720
things right.

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:06.890
And I have to tell you, I
don't think our behavior

00:20:06.890 --> 00:20:08.000
has changed at all.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.200
We just have a lot of very
bulging filing cabinets

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:13.350
because the collection
of information

00:20:13.350 --> 00:20:15.800
does not necessarily
produce wisdom,

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:17.390
but the collection
of information

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:21.340
can give you the illusion that
actually, you can play God.

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:25.150
Now that you've got all this
information, you're in charge.

00:20:25.150 --> 00:20:27.460
And of course, if
you've got information,

00:20:27.460 --> 00:20:28.680
that does give you power.

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:31.290
It gives you a lot
of power over anyone

00:20:31.290 --> 00:20:32.840
who doesn't have information.

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:35.740
But the real secret
is, how do you

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:40.300
select, arrange the information,
and how do you do so wisely?

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:43.670
In the New Testament,
that whole idea of wisdom,

00:20:43.670 --> 00:20:46.860
like so many other things
in the Old Testament,

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:51.180
comes forward and emerges,
not just as an abstract ideal,

00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:54.840
but as a person, because one
of the big categories that

00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:57.270
swirls around in
the New Testament

00:20:57.270 --> 00:21:01.600
is the idea that Jesus himself
is the embodiment of wisdom.

00:21:01.600 --> 00:21:04.590
Saint Paul says,
"In him are hidden

00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:08.690
all the treasures of wisdom
and knowledge," which is like--

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:09.630
how does that work?

00:21:09.630 --> 00:21:10.690
How does that cash out?

00:21:10.690 --> 00:21:12.590
Well, it doesn't
mean that if you

00:21:12.590 --> 00:21:14.320
know Jesus, that if
you're a Christian,

00:21:14.320 --> 00:21:17.090
you will suddenly become
a walking encyclopedia.

00:21:17.090 --> 00:21:20.190
It does mean, however, that if
you get to know Jesus and let

00:21:20.190 --> 00:21:24.110
him reshape your life, then
there is at least a chance that

00:21:24.110 --> 00:21:26.210
in some ways at
least to begin with,

00:21:26.210 --> 00:21:28.130
and hopefully more
as you go on, you

00:21:28.130 --> 00:21:32.070
will be making wise
choices about what

00:21:32.070 --> 00:21:35.760
from that world of information
to harvest, to deploy,

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:38.250
to do things with,
and in particular,

00:21:38.250 --> 00:21:40.620
how to use the
information wisely

00:21:40.620 --> 00:21:43.329
for the benefit of
the whole world,

00:21:43.329 --> 00:21:44.620
because that's the other thing.

00:21:44.620 --> 00:21:46.161
If you're just
gathering information,

00:21:46.161 --> 00:21:48.540
it can be so that you
can simply do whatever

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:51.940
you want to do and let the rest
of the world be as ill-informed

00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:52.840
as it wants.

00:21:52.840 --> 00:21:55.980
But the whole point of wisdom
in the Biblical tradition

00:21:55.980 --> 00:22:00.270
is about new creation,
that through wisdom, God

00:22:00.270 --> 00:22:04.790
wants to work through wise human
beings in every walk of life

00:22:04.790 --> 00:22:08.540
in order to bring
about healing, repair,

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:13.780
flourishing, wise human
societies, wise ecologies,

00:22:13.780 --> 00:22:17.480
wise ways of being
in the creation.

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:20.280
So the vision of good news,
of what happened in Jesus

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:23.740
and what will happen at the
end, catches us in between it.

00:22:23.740 --> 00:22:26.850
When Jesus came out of the
tomb on Easter morning,

00:22:26.850 --> 00:22:30.000
that was the beginning
of new creation.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.837
So many Christians think, well,
he rose again three days later.

00:22:32.837 --> 00:22:34.670
That's fine, so there
is a life after death,

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:35.860
so we're going to heaven.

00:22:35.860 --> 00:22:37.510
That's not the point.

00:22:37.510 --> 00:22:40.890
The point is that when
Jesus rose on the third day,

00:22:40.890 --> 00:22:44.240
this was the launch
of the new creation,

00:22:44.240 --> 00:22:47.880
with Jesus himself
as its first example

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:52.540
and as its active agent,
and God will do finally

00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:56.280
for the whole creation what
happened then at Easter

00:22:56.280 --> 00:22:58.020
with Jesus' resurrection.

00:22:58.020 --> 00:23:00.210
That's the Christian
good news, and I've

00:23:00.210 --> 00:23:02.890
suggested that as
we think about what

00:23:02.890 --> 00:23:07.320
it means to be genuinely human
within that vision, what we

00:23:07.320 --> 00:23:09.670
find is a vision
of Jesus himself

00:23:09.670 --> 00:23:12.370
as the embodiment
of wisdom giving us

00:23:12.370 --> 00:23:15.700
the human vocation, the
Solomonic vocation, if you

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:18.750
like-- yes, to have as
much information as we can.

00:23:18.750 --> 00:23:20.650
That's wonderful--
but then, also

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:25.610
to know how to use,
deploy, navigate it wisely

00:23:25.610 --> 00:23:29.110
for the benefit not just
of ourselves, but of God's

00:23:29.110 --> 00:23:31.820
