00:28:19.100 --> 00:28:23.580
wasn't primarily yay, now
we all get eternal life,

00:28:23.580 --> 00:28:26.960
but to launch this new
creation, of which Jesus is the,

00:28:26.960 --> 00:28:30.720
I think you said the acting
agent and the first example of.

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:31.480
N. T. WRIGHT: Put it close
to the mic [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:32.521
AUDIENCE: Oh, sure, yeah.

00:28:32.521 --> 00:28:34.640
From a Biblical
theology perspective,

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:38.070
usually, people consider the
cross the center of history.

00:28:38.070 --> 00:28:41.590
Would you say that instead, the
cross is typological of this

00:28:41.590 --> 00:28:43.715
greater thing that's actually
the center, or it's--

00:28:43.715 --> 00:28:44.714
N. T. WRIGHT: Thank you.

00:28:44.714 --> 00:28:45.400
That's good.

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:47.640
I knew in talking
for 25 minutes that I

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.240
was bound to give
hostages to fortune,

00:28:49.240 --> 00:28:52.070
and you just picked one of
them up, and that's fine.

00:28:52.070 --> 00:28:54.480
The cross and resurrection
go absolutely together.

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:56.030
The resurrection
means what it means

00:28:56.030 --> 00:28:58.890
because it is the resurrection
of the Jesus who was crucified.

00:28:58.890 --> 00:29:01.604
If somebody had just happened
to die and three days later be

00:29:01.604 --> 00:29:04.020
found to be alive again, that
wouldn't have meant anything

00:29:04.020 --> 00:29:05.160
like the same thing.

00:29:05.160 --> 00:29:08.120
Likewise, the cross means
what it means in relation

00:29:08.120 --> 00:29:09.090
to the resurrection.

00:29:09.090 --> 00:29:12.476
Nobody at 6:00 PM on Good
Friday was saying, well,

00:29:12.476 --> 00:29:13.892
we've always
believed that someone

00:29:13.892 --> 00:29:15.160
is going to die for
the sins of the world.

00:29:15.160 --> 00:29:16.450
So he's done it, and
yeah, it was messy,

00:29:16.450 --> 00:29:18.616
but it's OK because he'll
be-- no, they just weren't

00:29:18.616 --> 00:29:20.210
thinking like that at all.

00:29:20.210 --> 00:29:22.650
They were absolutely
devastated and distraught,

00:29:22.650 --> 00:29:26.020
and the resurrection
compelled a total reevaluation

00:29:26.020 --> 00:29:28.900
of the meaning of
what just happened.

00:29:28.900 --> 00:29:30.510
There are 1,000 ways
you can say this,

00:29:30.510 --> 00:29:32.230
but pretty essential
is that they

00:29:32.230 --> 00:29:36.180
came to believe that if Jesus
had been raised from the dead,

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:39.190
this meant that Death itself--
Death with a capital D,

00:29:39.190 --> 00:29:42.450
If you like-- had somehow
strangely been overcome,

00:29:42.450 --> 00:29:44.320
been beaten, been defeated.

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:46.530
And then they said,
wait a minute.

00:29:46.530 --> 00:29:49.770
All those strange things
Jesus had said and done

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:52.650
about his own forthcoming death,
which we didn't understand

00:29:52.650 --> 00:29:57.280
at the time-- maybe that
was about that on the cross,

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:01.650
he was going to do that
somehow defeating of death

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:03.830
and of the evil
which causes death.

00:30:03.830 --> 00:30:07.990
And so you get growing up very
early in Christianity theories

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:10.760
about how the cross means
what it means in relation

00:30:10.760 --> 00:30:11.800
to the resurrection.

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:14.540
And so because the
cross has defeated

00:30:14.540 --> 00:30:17.112
the power of evil and
of death, then Jesus

00:30:17.112 --> 00:30:19.320
is raised from the dead,
which wouldn't have happened

00:30:19.320 --> 00:30:21.440
otherwise, and
then a new world is

00:30:21.440 --> 00:30:24.250
opened, in which
humans can be rescued

00:30:24.250 --> 00:30:27.450
from evil, and sin, and
death, and ultimately,

00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:28.450
the whole creation.

00:30:28.450 --> 00:30:30.870
So that's broadly how
it works, though it

00:30:30.870 --> 00:30:34.330
takes large volumes of
theology to spell all that out

00:30:34.330 --> 00:30:34.926
and exegesis.

00:30:34.926 --> 00:30:36.550
Does that-- do you
see what I'm saying?

00:30:36.550 --> 00:30:37.320
AUDIENCE: Yes, thanks.

00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:38.445
N. T. WRIGHT: Good, thanks.

00:30:38.445 --> 00:30:39.512
OK, next question.

00:30:39.512 --> 00:30:41.220
AUDIENCE: This is
picking up a little bit

00:30:41.220 --> 00:30:44.120
off the woman from Ireland.

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:45.880
We live in Silicon
Valley in 2015,

00:30:45.880 --> 00:30:48.310
which is very different
from the Greco-Roman world

00:30:48.310 --> 00:30:51.710
of the first century, so
if we take the scriptures

00:30:51.710 --> 00:30:54.510
as authoritative, how do
we go beyond the scriptures

00:30:54.510 --> 00:31:00.782
to seek to live wisely in a
very different world today?

00:31:00.782 --> 00:31:01.990
N. T. WRIGHT: Great question.

00:31:01.990 --> 00:31:04.350
Yes, we do live in a
very different world,

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:07.207
and actually, people in the
third and fourth century

00:31:07.207 --> 00:31:09.290
lived in a very different
world from that of Jesus

00:31:09.290 --> 00:31:12.010
because the Jewish
bits of Jesus' world

00:31:12.010 --> 00:31:15.420
had more or less gone forever,
with AD 70, when Jerusalem was

00:31:15.420 --> 00:31:19.310
destroyed, and AD 135, when the
last great Jewish rebellion was

00:31:19.310 --> 00:31:20.610
put down by the Romans.

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:21.520
Everything changed.

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:25.070
And actually, as a result,
a lot of early Christians

00:31:25.070 --> 00:31:28.790
didn't understand some things
in the New Testament in the way

00:31:28.790 --> 00:31:31.790
that we can do up to
a point because we've

00:31:31.790 --> 00:31:35.290
got so much better information,
ironically, about early Judaism

00:31:35.290 --> 00:31:36.130
than they had.

00:31:36.130 --> 00:31:38.080
And the world has
changed again and again.

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:39.607
It changed in the Middle Ages.

00:31:39.607 --> 00:31:40.940
It changed with the Renaissance.

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:42.740
It changed with the
invention of printing.

00:31:42.740 --> 00:31:44.740
And obviously, what's
happened in Silicon Valley

00:31:44.740 --> 00:31:48.940
and elsewhere now is a
communications revolution

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:52.150
of at least the same magnitude
as the invention of printing,

00:31:52.150 --> 00:31:56.660
and probably a different
magnitude entirely as well.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:59.100
However, what you find
in the New Testament

00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:02.330
is a sketch of
pictures and stories

00:32:02.330 --> 00:32:06.400
about ultimate new creation,
about the ultimate coming

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:09.180
together of heaven
and Earth, and these

00:32:09.180 --> 00:32:13.490
are not meant as culture-bound
blueprints for what's

00:32:13.490 --> 00:32:16.800
going to happen but as
universal narratives,

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:19.970
just like some of the best
poems are universal narratives,

00:32:19.970 --> 00:32:21.450
pointing forwards.

00:32:21.450 --> 00:32:24.640
And I've often said all our
language about the future,

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:28.140
whether Jewish or Christian,
is a set of signposts

00:32:28.140 --> 00:32:30.046
pointing into a fog.

00:32:30.046 --> 00:32:32.170
They may be true signposts,
but they don't give you

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:33.628
a photographic--
they're not trying

00:32:33.628 --> 00:32:35.890
to give you a photographic
reproduction of what

00:32:35.890 --> 00:32:37.650
you should expect to find.

00:32:37.650 --> 00:32:40.770
What they are saying is that
there will come a time when

00:32:40.770 --> 00:32:46.280
heaven and Earth will be joined
together completely forever,

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:49.890
and that within that, there
will be a new world, which

00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:53.420
will be like the present one,
only much more so, much more

00:32:53.420 --> 00:32:56.940
flourishing, much more real,
so that the world itself,

00:32:56.940 --> 00:32:59.650
and us in particular--
we are at the present

00:32:59.650 --> 00:33:01.870
just a shadow of
our future selves.

00:33:01.870 --> 00:33:05.780
There's a real you that God
will make you and give you

00:33:05.780 --> 00:33:08.760
at the end that will
be recognizably you

00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:11.630
and just like you,
but so much more so.

00:33:11.630 --> 00:33:14.280
And that's what
resurrection is all about.

00:33:14.280 --> 00:33:16.540
So it seems to me that
though the culture's changed

00:33:16.540 --> 00:33:18.747
radically, and though
today's culture here

00:33:18.747 --> 00:33:20.580
is very different from
what you'd find, say,

00:33:20.580 --> 00:33:23.060
in many other parts of the
world today, India, or China,

00:33:23.060 --> 00:33:26.510
or wherever, the vision
of the New Testament

00:33:26.510 --> 00:33:29.690
is about the whole creation
and heaven and Earth not

00:33:29.690 --> 00:33:32.720
being miles apart from one
another but kind of overlapping

00:33:32.720 --> 00:33:35.750
and interlocking, and of that
being finally brought together.

00:33:35.750 --> 00:33:38.270
Within that, there
is this vision

00:33:38.270 --> 00:33:40.310
of human flourishing,
which I think does

00:33:40.310 --> 00:33:42.000
translate cross-culturally.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.350
And here's the point.

00:33:44.350 --> 00:33:48.100
Most of the Bible
is our back story,

00:33:48.100 --> 00:33:50.430
and it gives us little hints
as to where we're going.

00:33:50.430 --> 00:33:52.013
And as I've argued
in one of my books,

00:33:52.013 --> 00:33:53.630
"Scripture and the
Authority of God,"

00:33:53.630 --> 00:33:56.980
the Bible is like an
unfinished five-act play

00:33:56.980 --> 00:33:58.850
with little hints,
little sketches,

00:33:58.850 --> 00:34:02.050
as to what the last act, what
the last scene, looks like.

00:34:02.050 --> 00:34:04.350
But most of the
fifth act is missing,

00:34:04.350 --> 00:34:07.190
and our task, if we
want to be Biblical,

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:10.659
is so to know the previous
four acts and the beginning

00:34:10.659 --> 00:34:14.050
of the fifth one that
we can improvise wisely

00:34:14.050 --> 00:34:15.480
to get to the fifth one.

00:34:15.480 --> 00:34:18.280
And that involves a
lot of translating out

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.897
into different cultural
and historical situations.

00:34:21.897 --> 00:34:23.980
Does that scratch where
your question was itching?

00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:24.480
Yeah, good.

