saying these are actually

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:03.750
things which humans do
and humans need to do,

00:36:03.750 --> 00:36:08.180
and which are part of what it
means to be genuinely human,

00:36:08.180 --> 00:36:11.470
and which we-- maybe we
just can't imagine it yet.

00:36:11.470 --> 00:36:13.460
Maybe somebody here
is inventing a machine

00:36:13.460 --> 00:36:15.430
that will weep and forgive.

00:36:15.430 --> 00:36:17.820
But you know what I'm
saying, that yeah,

00:36:17.820 --> 00:36:20.250
artificial intelligence is
hugely important, no doubt

00:36:20.250 --> 00:36:21.610
hugely useful.

00:36:21.610 --> 00:36:23.560
There are many things--
and at every stage

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:27.080
of the technological advances
of the last 300 years,

00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:29.840
people have said, oh, dear,
are we making a Frankenstein,

00:36:29.840 --> 00:36:31.780
or are we doing a big monster?

00:36:31.780 --> 00:36:34.550
And I want to say, yeah,
that is often the problem.

00:36:34.550 --> 00:36:37.170
Some of the greatest historians
of the 20th century-- I'm

00:36:37.170 --> 00:36:39.690
thinking for instance of Herbert
Butterfield in Cambridge--

00:36:39.690 --> 00:36:43.575
