Durham, I would often

00:46:15.660 --> 00:46:19.470
find that my diary was
absolutely full wall to wall,

00:46:19.470 --> 00:46:23.420
and then I would get a phone
call saying that, say, one

00:46:23.420 --> 00:46:25.730
of the clergy-- a child had
just been killed in a road

00:46:25.730 --> 00:46:27.140
accident or something.

00:46:27.140 --> 00:46:28.848
I'd think, oh, I need
to go and see them.

00:46:28.848 --> 00:46:30.646
But look, I've got--
and then the secretary

00:46:30.646 --> 00:46:32.020
would say, oh, by
the way, I just

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:35.090
had a call that your 3 o'clock
appointment's just canceled.

00:46:35.090 --> 00:46:35.590
Right.

00:46:35.590 --> 00:46:35.860
Get in the car.

00:46:35.860 --> 00:46:37.180
We're going to see them.

00:46:37.180 --> 00:46:39.950
And that happened so
often in the seven years

00:46:39.950 --> 00:46:42.744
I was doing that job that I
thought that this actually--

00:46:42.744 --> 00:46:43.910
I'm being looked after here.

00:46:43.910 --> 00:46:46.890
I need to be there, and
so a space opens up.

00:46:46.890 --> 00:46:48.970
Now, I'm not saying that
I live a charmed life,

00:46:48.970 --> 00:46:49.940
because I don't.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:53.244
I'm not saying I'm always well
organized, because I'm not.

00:46:53.244 --> 00:46:54.910
I actually need my
wife in the front row

00:46:54.910 --> 00:46:59.620
to stare at me as though to say
you telling these nice stories

00:46:59.620 --> 00:47:00.620
about how it works out.

00:47:00.620 --> 00:47:02.260
You know perfectly
well it doesn't.

00:47:02.260 --> 00:47:03.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:03.610 --> 00:47:05.700
I have a lovely cartoon
framed in my room,

00:47:05.700 --> 00:47:09.210
which is of a bishop and his
wife driving away from church,

00:47:09.210 --> 00:47:11.180
and the bishop is
saying to his wife,

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:14.190
"Have you considered how much
more effective my sermon would

00:47:14.190 --> 00:47:16.943
have been if you
haven't yelled, 'ha!'"

00:47:16.943 --> 00:47:19.410
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:20.290
So there.

00:47:20.290 --> 00:47:22.420
AUDIENCE: You
mentioned in Ephesians

00:47:22.420 --> 00:47:25.090
at the very end, Chapter Six,
about the spiritual battle

00:47:25.090 --> 00:47:27.800
and the idea of
principalities and powers.

00:47:27.800 --> 00:47:30.375
And in Silicon Valley
and information

00:47:30.375 --> 00:47:33.870
and technique and everything,
between information and wisdom,

00:47:33.870 --> 00:47:36.705
what is the battle in
terms of our relationship

00:47:36.705 --> 00:47:39.607
to principalities and powers
as it relates to this context?

00:47:39.607 --> 00:47:41.190
N. T. WRIGHT: That's
a great question,

00:47:41.190 --> 00:47:43.040
and I'm not sure that
I'm the right person

00:47:43.040 --> 00:47:45.039
to answer it because I
don't live and work here,

00:47:45.039 --> 00:47:46.460
and I really don't know.

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:50.500
I would guess, however, that
there are enormous forces

00:47:50.500 --> 00:47:53.990
in economics, in
technology, in America,

00:47:53.990 --> 00:47:56.350
in the Western world
in general, where you

00:47:56.350 --> 00:47:58.140
do want to ask the question.

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:00.171
We all have to
ask this question.

00:48:00.171 --> 00:48:02.420
I, as an academic teaching
students and writing books,

00:48:02.420 --> 00:48:03.690
have to answer the question.

00:48:03.690 --> 00:48:06.170
Are we actually going to work
to build the Tower of Babel?

00:48:06.170 --> 00:48:07.460
Is that what we're doing?

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:11.920
An all-human work is always
in danger of arrogance.

00:48:11.920 --> 00:48:14.460
That's why when you think
about the problem in the world,

00:48:14.460 --> 00:48:16.100
don't just look
at Genesis Three.

00:48:16.100 --> 00:48:19.100
Look at Genesis 3
through to Genesis 11

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:22.840
because here's the thing.

00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:27.200
The human task in the
beginning is about community.

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:29.010
It's about
replenishing the Earth,

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:32.390
about doing community,
about family, about land,

00:48:32.390 --> 00:48:35.570
about getting this
stuff sorted out.

00:48:35.570 --> 00:48:38.360
After Adam and Eve rebel,
whatever that means,

00:48:38.360 --> 00:48:40.620
picture language, et cetera,
one of the first things

00:48:40.620 --> 00:48:43.950
that happened is the first
murder-- Cain murdering Abel.

00:48:43.950 --> 00:48:46.375
But then, when Cain goes
off, what does he do?

00:48:46.375 --> 00:48:48.100
He builds a city.

00:48:48.100 --> 00:48:50.920
He still knows that
doing human community

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:53.510
is the thing you're
supposed to do.

00:48:53.510 --> 00:48:58.000
But what happens to the city--
not his city, but later on--

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.030
is that the city
becomes arrogant.

00:49:00.030 --> 00:49:01.500
Let's build a tower.

00:49:01.500 --> 00:49:02.830
The top reaches to heaven.

00:49:02.830 --> 00:49:04.920
And then, we will be it.

00:49:04.920 --> 00:49:06.940
We will be the people.

00:49:06.940 --> 00:49:11.020
And God comes down and
spoils it all, of course.

00:49:11.020 --> 00:49:15.430
And so there's a sense
that all human projects

00:49:15.430 --> 00:49:18.220
have the capacity to turn
into the Tower of Babel.

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:20.510
And if somebody sees
that going on and says,

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:21.420
hey, wait a minute.

00:49:21.420 --> 00:49:23.630
We're just doing this because
we want to be powerful.

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:24.421
We want to be rich.

00:49:24.421 --> 00:49:26.630
We want to be arrogant
and rule the world.

00:49:26.630 --> 00:49:29.410
Then if somebody is
calling time on that,

00:49:29.410 --> 00:49:32.560
blowing the whistle on that,
that's a very dangerous place

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:35.080
to be because when--
OK, here's the thing.

00:49:35.080 --> 00:49:38.350
When humans worship
that which is not God,

00:49:38.350 --> 00:49:42.100
whether it's power, or money,
or sex, or whatever it is,

00:49:42.100 --> 00:49:46.760
humans give to that dark
force, which we loosely

00:49:46.760 --> 00:49:51.970
label like that, the power
which we ought to have,

00:49:51.970 --> 00:49:54.720
but which in fact we're
giving to these forces.

00:49:54.720 --> 00:49:56.754
We call them forces.

00:49:56.754 --> 00:49:57.920
We don't have good language.

00:49:57.920 --> 00:49:59.840
They didn't have good language
for it in the ancient world.

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:02.470
We don't in today's world
because it's actually not

00:50:02.470 --> 00:50:05.200
really nameable.

00:50:05.200 --> 00:50:08.870
And then, these
forces rule over us.

00:50:08.870 --> 00:50:11.550
And if we get in their
way, they will crush us.

00:50:11.550 --> 00:50:14.920
But that doesn't absolve
us from the responsibility

00:50:14.920 --> 00:50:17.370
of naming the problems
that we're up against.

00:50:17.370 --> 00:50:19.870
So I'm not saying that Silicon
Valley is the Tower of Babel.

00:50:19.870 --> 00:50:20.412
It isn't.

00:50:20.412 --> 00:50:22.870
There's so many good things
that happen as a result of what

00:50:22.870 --> 00:50:23.650
you guys do.

00:50:23.650 --> 00:50:25.990
But every human
enterprise, including

00:50:25.990 --> 00:50:28.370
the one that I work
in, has the capacity

00:50:28.370 --> 00:50:31.240
to become self-idolatrous,
Babel-like,

00:50:31.240 --> 00:50:34.230
and we have to name that and
deal with it as best we can,

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:35.710
preferably wisely.

00:50:35.710 --> 00:50:37.586
OK, time for probably
just one more question.

00:50:37.586 --> 00:50:38.085
I'm sorry.

00:50:38.085 --> 00:50:39.930
I'm seeing lots of
hands over there.

00:50:39.930 --> 00:50:46.140
I'm not running away immediately
afterwards, so well, OK.

00:50:46.140 --> 00:50:47.130
You got it.

00:50:47.130 --> 00:50:48.130
AUDIENCE: Oh, thank you.

00:50:48.130 --> 00:50:51.520
Your story-- you said about
the background of the gospel

00:50:51.520 --> 00:50:52.179
and your--

00:50:52.179 --> 00:50:53.720
N. T. WRIGHT: Hold
the microphone up.

00:50:53.720 --> 00:50:57.210
AUDIENCE: --your example of the
background story of the gospel,

00:50:57.210 --> 00:50:59.810
and you talked about
your story of rugby,

00:50:59.810 --> 00:51:01.460
and that's such a
great example for us

00:51:01.460 --> 00:51:04.020
here to realize that
if you don't understand

00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:07.130
the culture and the
passion that's behind that,

00:51:07.130 --> 00:51:09.480
it's hard to really
understand it coming from you.

00:51:09.480 --> 00:51:13.560
But those of us who've
experienced it of course

00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:14.652
can relate better.

00:51:14.652 --> 00:51:16.860
I've been trying to understand
the New Testament more

00:51:16.860 --> 00:51:21.660
accurately and studying Hebrew
idioms of the first century

00:51:21.660 --> 00:51:23.090
within Judaism.

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:25.060
It's really unified
the New Testament

00:51:25.060 --> 00:51:27.320
and connected it to the old.

00:51:27.320 --> 00:51:30.260
Even better, I'm wondering about
your studies of Hebrew idioms

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:32.360
within first century Judaism.

00:51:32.360 --> 00:51:34.799
Paul uses them
throughout his Epistles.

00:51:34.799 --> 00:51:36.340
You find it through
the Book of Acts,

00:51:36.340 --> 00:51:37.970
and it's clarified a lot for me.

00:51:37.970 --> 00:51:39.589
I'm wonder about
your studies in that.

00:51:39.589 --> 00:51:41.630
N. T. WRIGHT: Yeah, this
is a technical question,

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:45.350
so let me just give
a brief answer.

00:51:45.350 --> 00:51:47.870
Every generation in the
church, at its best,

00:51:47.870 --> 00:51:51.160
has known that you need
to understand the Bible

00:51:51.160 --> 00:51:53.300
in its original context.

00:51:53.300 --> 00:51:56.930
Now, of course, you then need
to live it in your own context,

00:51:56.930 --> 00:51:59.640
and there's always a
dialogue between those two.

00:51:59.640 --> 00:52:01.210
I am one of the
lucky ones who's been

00:52:01.210 --> 00:52:03.800
able to spend my lifestyle
studying-- I was trained

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:07.200
as an ancient historian
before I was a theologian,

00:52:07.200 --> 00:52:10.287
so I love going back
into the first century

00:52:10.287 --> 00:52:12.370
and trying to make sense
of what's going on there,

00:52:12.370 --> 00:52:16.091
and that means the languages,
the texts, et cetera.

00:52:16.091 --> 00:52:18.340
Particularly-- I'll just
give you one example of that,

00:52:18.340 --> 00:52:22.590
because then we must stop-- the
way that other first century

00:52:22.590 --> 00:52:26.110
Jews, or the ways that other
first century Jews were reading

00:52:26.110 --> 00:52:29.350
their scriptures, are
absolutely fascinating

00:52:29.350 --> 00:52:32.580
and help us to see how
the early Christians then

00:52:32.580 --> 00:52:35.760
were reading the same scriptures
in the light of what had just

00:52:35.760 --> 00:52:37.890
happened to Jesus.

00:52:37.890 --> 00:52:40.540
And there's all sorts of
overlap and interplay.

00:52:40.540 --> 00:52:41.890
Take the Dead Sea Scrolls.

00:52:41.890 --> 00:52:44.570
The Dead Sea Scrolls-- you
have a lot of scrolls which are

00:52:44.570 --> 00:52:46.550
simply exegesis of scripture.

00:52:46.550 --> 00:52:50.000
They take [INAUDIBLE],
one of the other prophets

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.800
or the psalms, and
they do exegesis,

00:52:52.800 --> 00:52:54.530
and they apply it
to their own day.

00:52:54.530 --> 00:52:56.270
And we can see the
early Christians

00:52:56.270 --> 00:52:58.940
doing the same thing, except
in the light of Jesus.

00:52:58.940 --> 00:53:02.320
And that's a fascinating
exercise, which sometimes comes

00:53:02.320 --> 00:53:05.580
very, very close, so close
that you'd think they're just

00:53:05.580 --> 00:53:07.080
looking over each
other's shoulders,

00:53:07.080 --> 00:53:09.490
and sometimes it's
quite different.

00:53:09.490 --> 00:53:11.880
One of the key things, of
course, being that many,

00:53:11.880 --> 00:53:14.340
many Jews-- not all--
in the first century

00:53:14.340 --> 00:53:17.470
believed that when God was
going to do what God was going

00:53:17.470 --> 00:53:18.990
to do for Israel
and the world, it

00:53:18.990 --> 00:53:23.930
would involve an actual battle,
a real bloodbath, a fight,

00:53:23.930 --> 00:53:26.450
and that God would lead them
in victory against the pagan

00:53:26.450 --> 00:53:26.950
hordes.

00:53:26.950 --> 00:53:30.700
It had happened before in 164
with the Maccabean Revolt,

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:32.380
and they hoped it
would happen again.

00:53:32.380 --> 00:53:35.850
One of the most important
things about the early Christian

00:53:35.850 --> 00:53:39.060
vision is that because they knew
Jesus, the crucified and risen

00:53:39.060 --> 00:53:42.880
one, when they talk about the
battle which is going to come,

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:46.160
it's not one which humans will
fight in the ordinary way,

00:53:46.160 --> 00:53:47.930
hence the sermon on the mount.

00:53:47.930 --> 00:53:51.500
When God becomes king, he
doesn't send in the tanks.

00:53:51.500 --> 00:53:53.410
He sends in the meek,
and the mourners,

00:53:53.410 --> 00:53:55.785
and the brokenhearted, and
the hungry-for-justice people,

00:53:55.785 --> 00:53:56.710
and the peacemakers.

00:53:56.710 --> 00:53:59.640
That's how God's kingdom
comes on Earth as in heaven.

00:53:59.640 --> 00:54:02.980
And we still have quite a lot
to do to learn about that stuff.

